Predicting if Glass is from a Building

Ainsley Carlson

2025-11-30

1 Introduction

Observations in the dataset come from 214 pieces of glass collected to predict if they are a type of float glass or not based on the makeup of different elements and their reflextive index. Prediction ability would help aid in criminal investigations as the glass can be used as evidence if correctly identified.

1.1 Variable Description

RI [Numeric]: refractive index

Na [Numeric]: Sodium weight percent in corresponding oxide

Mg [Numeric]: Magnesium weight percent in corresponding oxide

Al [Numeric]: Aluminum weight percent in corresponding oxide

Si [Numeric]: Silicon weight percent in corresponding oxide

K [Numeric]: Potassium weight percent in corresponding oxide

Ca [Numeric]: Calcium weight percent in corresponding oxide

Ba [Numeric]: Barium weight percent in corresponding oxide

Fe [Numeric]: Iron weight percent in corresponding oxide

Type [Categorical]: Glass type where type=1 & type=2 are building windows, type=3, & type=4 are vehicle windows, type=5 is containers, type=6 is tableware, and type=7 is headlamps.

Building [binary]: If the glass comes from a building or not, used for binary prediction variable.

Data Source: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/42/glass+identification

There are no missing values in this data and all variables appear to have plausible values, so no feature engineering will be needed for this data analysis. Looking at the correlation matrix between the feture variables shows that the reflection index is highly correlated with calcium and moderately correlated with silicon. Approximately 68.22% of the glass types were from buildings .

For the elements sodium, magnesium, aluminum, potassium, and barium all have distinctive peaks in densities at different points for glass from buildings and not from buildings. This indicates that they could be strong predictors of glass type. For iron, the density distributions are very similar for if the glass is from a building or not with the main difference being that the majority of glass with an iron weight percent greater than 0.1 percent is building glass. For refractive index, calcium and silicon there are no distinctive differences in the density curves between building glass and non-building glass.

For principal component vectors one and eight the refractive index is the major contributor to the vector, so the eight vector is likely repetitive and will not be needed. Other major contributors include magnesium for the second vector, iron for the fifth vector, barium for the sixth vector, potassium for the seventh vector, and calcium for the ninth vector. The third principal component vector did not have any major contributors to it. Sodium and aluminum are not major contributors to any of the principal component vectors.

Looking at the proportion each PCA contributes to the variance shows the eigth and ninth principal components each contribute less than 1% to the total variance, so we can conclude that they are not contributing a significant amount of information overall. Additionally, it is clear that PC6 and PC7 contribute less than 5% to the overall proportion of variance. However, including PC6 increases the proportion of variance explained from about 90% to 95%, so I will include the first six principal components in my analysis to ensure I lose no more than 5% of the information if all principal components were included.

screeplot(gl.pca, 
          type = "lines",
          main = "Scree Plot of PCA Glass Features")

Looking at the scree plot shows that the difference in variance of the components drops steeply between the first three components before having moderate drops in variance between the third and sixth components. After the sixth component the variance start to level off and are close to zero. The scree plot reaffirms the decision to include up to the sixth principal component into the analysis.

4 Clustering Analysis

For the clustering analysis on variables I will apply K-means centroid algorithm between the variables of the refractive index and calcium as they had the highest correlation between any two of the feature variables.

clust.data = glass[, c("RI", "Ca")]
scaled.data = as.data.frame(scale(clust.data)[,1:2])
k2 <- kmeans(x = scaled.data, 
             centers = 2, 
             iter.max = 10,
             nstart = 25,
             algorithm = "Lloyd", #"Hartigan-Wong",
             trace = FALSE)

4.1 K-Means Clustering

4.1.1 Elbow Point Graph

wss = NULL
K = 15
for (i in 1:K){
  wss[i] = kmeans(scaled.data, i, 1 )$tot.withinss
 }
## elbow plot
plot(1:K, wss, type ="b",
          col= "#648FFF",
          xlab="Number of Clusters",
          ylab = "WSS",
          main = "Elbow Plot for Selecting Optimal Number of Clusters")

The elbow plot above shows the ideal number of clusters to be about 4 as the the WSS does not have any more consistent decreases as the number of clusters gets to be above 4. In some valuations of the clusters centers, there is an increase in the WSS score going from 4 to 5 clusters, verifying 4 clusters is the ideal number of clusters.

4.1.2 Groups Visualized

colors<- c("#785EF0","#DC267F", "#FE6100", "#FFB000")
k4 <- kmeans(x = scaled.data, 
             centers = 4, 
             iter.max = 10,
             nstart = 25,

             trace = FALSE)

# Legend

       legend = levels(factor(scaled.data$group)),
       pch = 19,

Performing a K-means clustering shows that cluster 3 is very distinct from the rest of the clusters. A little less distinct is cluster 1, but the grouping makes sense as almost all the observations have a refractive index between 0 and 2 along with being between 0 to 2 percent of weight for calcium. Groups 2 and 4 do not have as clear cut groupings as some of the upper right values of group two look like they could be closer or in group 4. However, as stated before increasing clusters will not increase the distinction between the groups and decreasing to 3 clusters will not help either.

5 Local Outlier Factor (LOF)

The LOF is a method to identify possible local outliers and can be used as an engineered variable to help improve model prediction accuracy.

5.1 LOF of PCAs of Interest

log.glass = glass[,c(1:9)]+1   # drop the categorical variable in the original 
                            # data set and transform all numerical to the
                            # log-scale
glass.pca <- prcomp(log.glass, center = TRUE, scale = FALSE)
# use the first two PCs to define a data frame for LOF
pca.glass = data.frame(glass.pca$x[, 1:6])
### Calculate the two LOF scores with the original variables and PCs respectively.
lof.pca <- lof(pca.glass, minPts = 30)  # minPts = k value, number of nearest neighbors
lof.orig <- lof(log.glass, minPts = 30)
## 2D plot of LOF score based on PCs
plot(pca.glass, pch = "x",    # point symbol
     main = "LOF Based on PCA", 
     #asp = 1,
     cex = 0.5)                # aspect ratio - ratio of 'y/x'
points(pca.glass, 
       cex = (lof.pca-1)*1.5,      # point size according to the LOF score
       pch = 21, 
       col = "#785EF0")
text(pca.glass[lof.pca > 1.8,], 
     labels = round(lof.pca, 1)[lof.pca > 1.8], 
     pos = 1,   # 1, 2, 3 and 4 => below, left , above, and right 
     cex = 0.7,
     col = "#DC267F")

Looking at the plots of the principal components in the column with PC$ there appear to be outliers on the left side of the graph, with values less than -2 on the x-axis. Additionally, PC1 and PC6 also appear to skew slightly to the left with PC6 having prominent outliers like PC4.

5.2 LOF Score Comparison

plot(lof.pca, lof.orig, pch ="x", 
     main = "LOF Scores Comparison: PCA vs Original Variable",
     xlab = "PCA LOF Score",
     ylab = "Original LOF Score",
     cex = 0.6)
points(lof.pca[lof.pca > 1.8], lof.orig[lof.pca > 1.8],
       pch = 21, 
       cex = lof.pca*1.5,
       col = "#785EF0")
text(lof.pca[lof.pca > 1.8], lof.orig[lof.pca > 1.8], 
     labels = round(lof.pca, 1)[lof.pca > 1.8], 
     pos = 1,   # 1, 2, 3 and 4 => below, left , above, and right 
     cex = 0.7,
     col = "#DC267F")

The graph of the LOF score comparison shown above shows 6 extreme outliers, 3 of which are really far away from the cluster. Based on the extreme outliers, I imagine that LOF could help improve the model accuracy.

5.3 LOF Comparisons

lof.glass.10  <- lof(glass [, 1:9], minPts =75) 
lof.glass.50  <- lof(glass [,1:9], minPts = 85) 
lof.glass.100  <- lof(glass [, 1:9], minPts = 100) 
lof.glass.200  <- lof(glass [, 1:9], minPts = 150) 
  ROCobj.lof.10 <- roc(glass$isbuilding, lof.glass.10, direction = ">")
  ROCobj.lof.50 <- roc(glass$isbuilding, lof.glass.50, direction = ">")
  ROCobj.lof.100 <- roc(glass$isbuilding, lof.glass.100, direction = ">")
  ROCobj.lof.200 <- roc(glass$isbuilding, lof.glass.200, direction = ">")
  ##
  sen.LOF.10 = ROCobj.lof.10$sensitivities
  fnr.LOF.10 = 1 - ROCobj.lof.10$specificities
  ##
  sen.LOF.50 = ROCobj.lof.50$sensitivities
  fnr.LOF.50 = 1 - ROCobj.lof.50$specificities
  ##
  sen.LOF.100 = ROCobj.lof.100$sensitivities
  fnr.LOF.100 = 1 - ROCobj.lof.100$specificities
  ##
  sen.LOF.200 = ROCobj.lof.200$sensitivities
  fnr.LOF.200 = 1 - ROCobj.lof.200$specificities
par(type="s")
colors = c("#785EF0","#DC267F", "#FE6100", "#FFB000")
plot(fnr.LOF.10, sen.LOF.10, type = "l", lwd = 2, col = colors[1],
     xlim = c(0,1),
     ylim = c(0,1),
     xlab = "1 - specificity",
     ylab = "sensitivity",
     main = "ROC Curves of LOF Detection Comparison")
lines(fnr.LOF.50, sen.LOF.50, lwd = 2, lty = 2, col = colors[2])
lines(fnr.LOF.100, sen.LOF.100, lwd = 1, col = colors[3])
lines(fnr.LOF.200, sen.LOF.200, lwd = 1, col = colors[4])

segments(0,0,1,1, lwd =1, col = "#648FFF", lty = 2)
legend("topleft", c("LOF.75", "LOG.85", "LOF.100", "LOF.150"), 
       col=colors, lwd=c(2,2,1,1,1),
       lty=c(1,2,1,1,2), bty = "n", cex = 0.7)

##
AUC.10 = ROCobj.lof.10$auc
AUC.50 = ROCobj.lof.50$auc
AUC.100 = ROCobj.lof.100$auc
AUC.200 = ROCobj.lof.200$auc
text(0.87, 0.25, paste("AUC.75 = ", round(AUC.10,4)), col=colors[1], cex = 0.7, adj = 1)
text(0.87, 0.20, paste("AUC.85 = ", round(AUC.50,4)), col=colors[2], cex = 0.7, adj = 1)
text(0.87, 0.15, paste("AUC.100 = ", round(AUC.100,4)), col=colors[3], cex = 0.7, adj = 1)
text(0.87, 0.10, paste("AUC.150 = ", round(AUC.200,4)), col=colors[4], cex = 0.7, adj = 1)

Based on the AUC scores of the different minimum neighbor requirements, the LOF with 75 nearest neighbors is the one that performs the best. It appears that after 75, the AUC starts to slowly decrease as the number of nearest neighbors increases. This is a scenario where bootstrapping may help differentiate, but given how close the scores are even boostrapping the different LOFs may not provide a clear best LOF. Additionally, the data only has 214 values, so it may be best to stay with a smaller number of nearest neighbors.

6.2 Bootstrapping Final Model

btAUClog.vec = c()
## Select the number of bootstrap samples to be generated
B = 1000
## Size of the original sample
sample.size = dim(glass)[1]
## Vector of cut-off probabilities for construct ROC
cut.off.seq = seq(0,1, length = 100)
# bootstrap procedure starts here
for (k in 1:B){
  boot.id = sample(1:sample.size, sample.size, replace = TRUE)   # Bootstrap IDs
  boot.sample = glass[boot.id,]      # Bootstrap samples         
  ## Bootstrap logistic regression model is given below
  boot.logistic = glm(isbuilding~Mg +Na+Al+RI, family = binomial, data = boot.sample)
  ##
  pred.prob = predict.glm(boot.logistic, newdata = boot.sample, type = "response")
  ## vectors to store sensitivity and specificity
  sensitivity.vec = NULL
  specificity.vec = NULL
    for (i in 1:100){
   pred.building = as.numeric(pred.prob > cut.off.seq[i])
   ### components for defining various measures
   TN = sum(pred.building == 0 & boot.sample$isbuilding == 0)
   FN = sum(pred.building == 0 & boot.sample$isbuilding == 1)
   FP = sum(pred.building == 1 & boot.sample$isbuilding == 0)
   TP = sum(pred.building == 1 & boot.sample$isbuilding == 1)
   ###
   sensitivity.vec[i] = TP / (TP + FN)
   specificity.vec[i] = TN / (TN + FP)
  }
  one.minus.spec = 1 - specificity.vec
  sens.vec = sensitivity.vec
  ## A better approx of ROC, need library {pROC}
  prediction = pred.prob
  category = boot.sample$isbuilding == 1
  ROCobj <- roc(category, prediction)
  btAUClog.vec[k] = round(auc(ROCobj),4)
}

7 Conclusion

In terms of AUC score, the model with engineered features performed slightly better than the model without. It is interesting to note that sodium was included in both models despite not being a significant contributor to any of the principal components. Refractive index was also in both models, but in the form of the principal component for the model with the engineered variables. For this data in particular I do not believe that feature engineering providing enough model improvement to be worth the effort to create all the features.

Creating a model without engineered values is much simpler as all that is needed is not ensure the data is clean and usable before performing a step-wise regression between the intercept only model and the model with all variables to find the best model. With feature engineering, there is a lot more work and it is more based on personal judgement when creating the engineered variable. I think feature engineering provides the most impact with models that need a large improvement in their AUC scores, and/or using the data with variables that are not close to being normally distributed. There may also be ways to make the process of engineering features less based on personal judgement, but some personal discretion may always be needed.
